  "Expressing the vector as a product of two scalars": "",
  "Writing the vector as a single number representing its length": "",
  "Writing the vector as an angle only": "",
  "Expressing the vector using its horizontal and vertical components as an ordered pair <a, b>": "",
  "The component form of a 2D vector writes it as <a, b> where a is the horizontal (x) component and b is the vertical (y) component. This fully specifies the vector's magnitude and direction.": "",
  "What does it mean for two vectors to be equal?": "",
  "They have the same magnitude only": "",
  "They have the same magnitude and the same direction": "",
  "They have the same direction only": "",
  "They start at the same point": "",
  "Two vectors are equal if and only if they have both the same magnitude and the same direction, which means their corresponding components are equal. Position (starting point) does not matter for free vectors.": "",
  "What is the resultant of two vectors?": "",
  "The difference of their magnitudes": "",
  "The angle between the two vectors": "",
  "The single vector that has the same effect as the two vectors combined (their sum)": "",
  "The product of their magnitudes": "",
  "The resultant of two vectors is their vector sum, which is the single vector that produces the same effect as applying both vectors together. Graphically, it is found using the parallelogram law or tip-to-tail method.": "",
  "What is the direction angle of a vector?": "",
  "The angle measured counterclockwise from the positive x-axis to the vector": "",
  "Half the magnitude of the vector": "",
  "The angle between the vector and the y-axis": "",
  "The angle between the vector and any other vector": "",
  "The direction angle theta of a vector is measured counterclockwise from the positive x-axis to the vector. For v = <a, b>, theta = arctan(b/a), adjusted for the correct quadrant.": "",
  "What is the parallelogram law for vector addition?": "",
  "The sum of two parallel vectors is zero": "",
  "The sum of two vectors is always longer than either vector": "",
  "Vectors can only be added if they are perpendicular": "",
  "Place two vectors at the same initial point; their sum is the diagonal of the parallelogram they form": "",
  "The parallelogram law states that if two vectors share the same initial point, their sum is the diagonal of the parallelogram formed by the two vectors as adjacent sides. This gives the same result as the tip-to-tail method.": "",
  "A pilot flies a plane at 300 mph heading due north, but a crosswind blows at 40 mph due east. What is the magnitude of the plane's resultant velocity?": "",
  "260 mph": "",
  "sqrt(90400) ≈ 302.7 mph": "",
  "340 mph": "",
  "sqrt(80000) ≈ 282.8 mph": "",
  "The plane's velocity is <0, 300> and the wind is <40, 0>. Resultant = <40, 300>. Magnitude = sqrt(40^2 + 300^2) = sqrt(1600 + 90000) = sqrt(91600) ≈ 302.7 mph. The wind slightly increases the speed while pushing the plane off course.": "",
  "Two tugboats pull a barge. Tugboat A exerts a force of 5000 N at 30 degrees from the forward direction, and Tugboat B exerts 5000 N at -30 degrees. What is the resultant force?": "",
  "5000sqrt(3) N forward": "",
  "5000sqrt(3) ≈ 8660 N forward": "",
  "5000 N forward": "",
  "10000 N forward": "",
  "Tugboat A: <5000cos(30°), 5000sin(30°)> = <2500sqrt(3), 2500>. Tugboat B: <5000cos(-30°), 5000sin(-30°)> = <2500sqrt(3), -2500>. Sum = <5000sqrt(3), 0>. The lateral forces cancel, giving 5000sqrt(3) ≈ 8660 N straight forward.": "",
  "A hiker walks 4 km east, then 3 km at a bearing of N30°E (60° from east). What is the magnitude of her total displacement?": "",
  "7 km": "",
  "sqrt(25 + 12sqrt(3)) ≈ 6.08 km": "",
  "5 km": "",
  "sqrt(37 + 12sqrt(3)) ≈ 6.75 km": "",
  "First leg: <4, 0>. Second leg: <3cos(60°), 3sin(60°)> = <1.5, 1.5sqrt(3)>. Total: <5.5, 1.5sqrt(3)>. Magnitude = sqrt(5.5^2 + (1.5sqrt(3))^2) = sqrt(30.25 + 6.75) = sqrt(37) ≈ 6.08 km. Actually more precisely: sqrt((4+1.5)^2 + (1.5sqrt(3))^2) = sqrt(30.25 + 6.75) = sqrt(37) ≈ 6.08 km.": "",
  "A swimmer can swim at 2 m/s in still water and wants to cross a river that flows at 1.5 m/s. If she aims directly across, what angle does her actual path make with the line straight across?": "",
  "arctan(2/1.5) ≈ 53.13 degrees downstream": "",
  "45 degrees downstream": "",
  "30 degrees downstream": "",
  "arctan(1.5/2) ≈ 36.87 degrees downstream": "",
  "Her velocity across is 2 m/s and the river pushes her downstream at 1.5 m/s. The angle from straight across is arctan(downstream/across) = arctan(1.5/2) ≈ 36.87 degrees.": "",
  "An object is suspended by two cables making angles of 45° and 60° with the horizontal. If the object weighs 100 N, what is the tension T1 in the cable at 45°? (Use the equilibrium condition: T1 sin(45°) + T2 sin(60°) = 100 and T1 cos(45°) = T2 cos(60°))": "",
  "T1 ≈ 51.8 N": "",
  "T1 = 100/(sin(45°) + sin(60°)cos(45°)/cos(60°)) ≈ 51.8 N": "",
  "T1 ≈ 73.2 N": "",
  "T1 = 50 N": "",
  "From T1 cos(45°) = T2 cos(60°): T2 = T1 cos(45°)/cos(60°) = T1(sqrt(2)/2)/(1/2) = T1 sqrt(2). Substituting: T1(sqrt(2)/2) + T1 sqrt(2)(sqrt(3)/2) = 100, so T1 sqrt(2)(1 + sqrt(3))/2 = 100. T1 = 200/(sqrt(2)(1+sqrt(3))) ≈ 200/(2.732*1.414) ≈ 51.8 N.": "",
